the implication here is just most wasted time  

184
00:15:20,880 --> 00:15:25,840
is on building things nobody actually ends up 
wanting or using. So, the sooner you at least  

185
00:15:25,840 --> 00:15:30,600
get directional sense of are you heading 
in a good direction, the faster it all go?

186
00:15:30,600 --> 00:15:31,760
Yeah, totally.

187
00:15:31,760 --> 00:15:37,240
I imagine a criticism you all get. People are 
like, "Yes, Linear is so great, so beautiful,  

188
00:15:37,240 --> 00:15:42,760
so much better than what's been out there for 
decades," but over time you'll probably become  

189
00:15:42,760 --> 00:15:46,560
a bloated piece of software as well. That's 
just the fate of enterprise software. You  

190
00:15:46,560 --> 00:15:51,160
have to check all these checkboxes. IT teams need 
all these features. So, there's always this like,  

191
00:15:51,160 --> 00:15:55,280
"Oh, yeah, sure, you guys can operate this way 
for now. You have an amazing product for now,  

192
00:15:55,280 --> 00:16:00,440
but it'll get ugly and bloated." How do 
you think about avoiding that? I know it's  

193
00:16:00,440 --> 00:16:04,200
something you spent a lot of time thinking 
about. Maybe give us a glimpse into some of  

194
00:16:04,200 --> 00:16:07,200
the conversations you have internally when 
there's these feature requests like, "Oh,  

195
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:11,160
I need single sign-on with this thing and this 
button here." How do you think about what to add,  

196
00:16:11,160 --> 00:16:14,480
what not to add, and how to add these 
features to not make it bloated?

197
00:16:14,480 --> 00:16:19,840
This question actually comes to us a lot from 
candidates that are interviewing with us. When you  

198
00:16:19,840 --> 00:16:24,400
go like, "Hey, do you have any questions for us?" 
This is the question that we're going to get. So,  

199
00:16:24,400 --> 00:16:31,680
we hear it quite a lot, and it's very sensible 
for them to ask it because they see history being  

200
00:16:32,480 --> 00:16:37,920
littered with the corpses of startups trying 
to compete in this space and not making it,  

201
00:16:37,920 --> 00:16:46,840
and I think when we examine this problem, we 
look at, "Well, what kind of feature requests  

202
00:16:46,840 --> 00:16:53,080
can we debate and what kind of feature requests 
do we absolutely have to say no to?" And the  

203
00:16:53,080 --> 00:16:59,240
stuff that we absolutely have to say no to is 
also the exact kind of thing that leads to this  

204
00:16:59,240 --> 00:17:06,480
bloatedness that makes ICs hate their lives, 
and it's very specific. It's customization  

205
00:17:06,480 --> 00:17:13,160
features requested by middle managers in 
order to make reporting a little bit easier  

206
00:17:13,160 --> 00:17:18,720
at the cost of making IC workflows worse.
It's like if it fits that description,  

207
00:17:18,720 --> 00:17:22,680
we're just saying, "No." There's no debate 
because we've already thought about it and  

208
00:17:22,680 --> 00:17:27,600
this is the thing that we can't take a single 
step down this path. So, I think that's honestly  

209
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:33,280
one of the core promises of Linear is that we 
will not make this particular trade-off. So,  

210
00:17:33,280 --> 00:17:38,600
when you see people saying like, "Wow, Linear is 
so much faster. It's so much easier to use and it  

211
00:17:38,600 --> 00:17:43,120
makes my work so much more enjoyable." This is 
the reason because we have not taken a single step  

212
00:17:43,120 --> 00:17:52,440
in this direction. It's very easy for a PM to say 
yes to this kind of request because often they're  

213
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:56,440
talking with buyers. Any kind of B2B type of 
space, they're talking with whoever the gatekeeper  

214
00:17:56,440 --> 00:18:00,760
is and sales is putting pressure on them, and 
they're saying like, "Hey, we really want this one  

215
00:18:00,760 --> 00:18:06,360
feature. It's going to make our reporting nicer."
So, the director's going to be really excited by  

216
00:18:06,360 --> 00:18:10,160
this, and we'll definitely make a buying decision 
based off of this, and we have to convince them  

217
00:18:10,160 --> 00:18:14,920
that this is a false trade-off. The whole premise 
is wrong because the moment you start going down  

218
00:18:14,920 --> 00:18:21,680
this path, and you make the IC user experience 
worse, they're just going to disengage. No one  

219
00:18:21,680 --> 00:18:26,320
has to do this. If I'm an engineer, I get paid to 
write code. My performance review is based on my  

220
00:18:26,320 --> 00:18:30,000
code contribution. It's not based on like, 
"Did I fill in all the tickets right?" So,  

221
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:33,720
I'm just not going to do that part, or 
I'm going to do it very sporadically,  

222
00:18:33,720 --> 00:18:40,120
and then I'm going to just focus on my actual job.
And then all your reporting is wrong because all  

223
00:18:40,120 --> 00:18:47,360
the data is wrong, and it's sparse, and you get 
situations where people will... They'll say like,  

224
00:18:47,360 --> 00:18:52,560
"Well, here's a dropdown field that someone put 
in here that's required." There's nine choices.  

225
00:18:52,560 --> 00:18:55,560
I don't know what any of them meet, so I'm just 
going to pick one at random. I'm still going to  

226
00:18:55,560 --> 00:18:59,920
pick the first one. Also, I'm going to pray that 
my boss is not actually using this data to do any  

227
00:18:59,920 --> 00:19:05,840
kind of reporting and that has consequence because 
the data can't possibly be correct. So, I think  

228
00:19:05,840 --> 00:19:12,200
for us, it's a very easy decision when it comes 
to that particular category of feature request.

229
00:19:12,200 --> 00:19:13,920
I love how simple and clear that is. Basically,  

230
00:19:13,920 --> 00:19:19,000
you all have a policy. We'll prioritize ICs over 
middle managers. Especially, like I love that it's  

231
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:23,240
around reporting. Almost always it sounds 
like, "I want to track what's happening."

232
00:19:23,240 --> 00:19:25,000
Yeah, exactly. It's always, "I want 
to track what's happening." Well,  

233
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:31,200
what do you want to track? Well, I want 
to track which version of the product  

234
00:19:31,200 --> 00:19:37,200
this thing's tied to based on some field 
information. It's like, okay, how is the  

235
00:19:37,200 --> 00:19:40,960
person working on this supposed to even know that 
information? Well, it takes like a five-minute  

236
00:19:40,960 --> 00:19:43,880
scavenger hunt every single time. It's like, 
"I don't think they're going to do that, man."

237
00:19:43,880 --> 00:19:47,160
What I imagine happens, and I think 
why this is hard for most companies  

238
00:19:47,160 --> 00:19:52,360
is there's an implication that you're turning 
down deals. You're not adding that one feature  

239
00:19:52,360 --> 00:19:57,240
that will close a massive million-dollar 
sale, very difficult to do. I imagine it  

240
00:19:57,240 --> 00:20:01,120
helps a lot that... I imagine the COO is 
very bought into this and there's this,  

241
00:20:01,120 --> 00:20:05,760
"We will win long-term holding 
the line on this." Is that right?

242
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:12,520
So, it is, but I also think that there's not 
as much pressure as you would expect to do  

243
00:20:12,520 --> 00:20:18,120
these kinds of things. There are basic scaling 
things, like we had to make SAML and SCIM and  

244
00:20:18,120 --> 00:20:21,720
that kind of stuff. It's like, "Yeah, sure, we're 
going to do those sorts of, like keep the lights  

245
00:20:21,720 --> 00:20:28,440
on type of work," but when it comes to work 
that's related to the actual business logic of  

246
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:36,360
the app's value proposition, what buyers 
care about is, is this going to make their  

247
00:20:36,360 --> 00:20:40,320
team more effective? That's the reason that 
they're making this buying decision in the  

248
00:20:40,320 --> 00:20:43,640
first place is that they're like, "Well, 
the current situation we're in... " And  

249
00:20:43,640 --> 00:20:47,520
especially with large companies, right? 
The current situation we're in is a mess,  

250
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:52,240
and if we can convince them that these types of 
things are actually the reason that it's a mess,  

251
00:20:52,240 --> 00:20:57,040
then we can really navigate them out 
of wanting them in the first place.

252
00:20:57,040 --> 00:20:59,880
Got it. So, there's an element 
of you think you need this,  

253
00:20:59,880 --> 00:21:04,920
but it turns out you'll be more successful 
and get everything you want, not getting this?

254
00:21:04,920 --> 00:21:08,360
Yeah, and the thing is, it's not everything 
you want, right? Because people come with a  

255
00:21:08,360 --> 00:21:11,360
laundry list, and it's like laundry list. 
Here's 10 things I want. You're like,  

256
00:21:11,360 --> 00:21:14,680
"Do you want all of those 10 things equally?" 
They're like, "No, actually I don't." The first  

257
00:21:14,680 --> 00:21:18,800
three are the things that really matter to us. If 
we solve the first three, then the other stuff,  

258
00:21:18,800 --> 00:21:23,760
we can negotiate on. So, our job is to solve 
the first three-way better than anybody else  

259
00:21:23,760 --> 00:21:28,520
that if they got through the first three through 
some kind of visual programming, customization  

260
00:21:29,080 --> 00:21:33,280
type of thing, that it's never going 
to get to the quality level and the  

261
00:21:33,280 --> 00:21:36,960
depth that we're able to offer by 
offering those as native features.

262
00:21:36,960 --> 00:21:43,160
It's interesting thinking back to that survey 
I shared where the tool people want to switch  

263
00:21:43,160 --> 00:21:47,440
to if IT allowed them was Linear, and 
on the one hand you could argue, "Well,  

264
00:21:47,440 --> 00:21:52,000
okay, IT is not letting them use Linear for all 
these reasons. On the other hand, you guys are  

265
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:57,080
growing really quickly within enterprise, like 
you're a new business. You started, I think,  

266
00:21:57,080 --> 00:22:03,000
mid-market startups, and now you're working 
way up. So, I think it's not fair to say it's  

267
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:05,960
not going to work in enterprise. It's clearly 
working really well. I don't know if there's  

268
00:22:05,960 --> 00:22:10,960
any stats you can share anything of that, but 
it seems to be going well, expanding up market.

269
00:22:10,960 --> 00:22:16,040
Yeah, I mean, growth has been good. Growth in 
enterprise has been leading the other segments  

270
00:22:16,040 --> 00:22:21,120
because I think this year, especially we reached 
a tipping point where I think with software,  

271
00:22:21,120 --> 00:22:26,280
so much of the buying decision is 
based on almost like a brand thing,  

272
00:22:26,280 --> 00:22:32,560
like is this for us? A lot of times people 
pick "enterprise software." It's like,  

273
00:22:32,560 --> 00:22:36,480
"Why? You know everyone doesn't want this," 
and they're like, "Yeah, but it's for us."

274
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:39,840
You won't get fired for 
buying Microsoft or whatever.

275
00:22:39,840 --> 00:22:45,360
Yeah, exactly, and I think that we're starting to 
have enough brand penetration amongst enterprises  

276
00:22:45,360 --> 00:22:51,160
where people can have that feeling, right? They're 
like, "Hey, Linear is for us. Who are we? Well,  

277
00:22:51,160 --> 00:22:55,560
we are a large company that wants 
to act like a startup." It's like,  

278
00:22:55,560 --> 00:22:58,440
"Who doesn't want that? Who 
doesn't want to go fast?"

279
00:22:58,960 --> 00:23:03,240
Yeah. I had Jeffrey Moore on the podcast, 
and this is exactly what crossing the chasm  

280
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:07,160
looks like. He talked about basically you 
need someone that's across the chasm like a  

281
00:23:07,160 --> 00:23:12,680
later adopter that isn't the person that's, "I 
love new stuff, and I'm an early adopter kind  

282
00:23:12,680 --> 00:23:16,600
of evangelist." You need someone that's like 
traditional old school, takes their time to  

283
00:23:16,600 --> 00:23:21,600
start to adopt it for you to be like, "Oh, okay. 
Now, maybe I should really take it seriously."

284
00:23:21,600 --> 00:23:28,920
I also think that with this particular category 
of tool, and with a lot of other B2B software,  

285
00:23:28,920 --> 00:23:32,880
not... Like no means not now, right? 
Not right now because it doesn't fit  

286
00:23:32,880 --> 00:23:36,920
our budget. It doesn't fit our 
change management situation. "Oh,  

287
00:23:36,920 --> 00:23:43,280
we have this exec that's really wedded to this 
other tool," but those things change, right? So,  

288
00:23:43,280 --> 00:23:47,720
we keep in contact with them. They're in our CRM 
where we make sure we follow up, and we've had  

289
00:23:47,720 --> 00:23:53,920
a lot of these where we've been said no to, 
like two years ago, and now we have some new  

290
00:23:53,920 --> 00:23:58,440
features, and then go like, "Oh, yeah, it seems 
like you're ready for our scale," or whatever.

291
00:23:59,200 --> 00:24:02,080
You mentioned that when you have these 
debates and questions that come out,  

292
00:24:02,080 --> 00:24:05,800
you have features that a big company wants. 
There's this category of, "We know we will  

293
00:24:05,800 --> 00:24:10,680
not build things for middle managers that want 
reporting and custom stuff just to track what's  

294
00:24:10,680 --> 00:24:17,080
happening," versus something an IC wants to be 
more productive and successful, Linear. Give us  

295
00:24:17,080 --> 00:24:22,160
a little sense of some of the more complicated 
debates that aren't necessarily in that bucket.

296
00:24:22,160 --> 00:24:25,960
I think the complicated debates are often 
when we do add a new native feature,  

297
00:24:25,960 --> 00:24:29,840
do we extend an existing feature and make 
it more powerful or do we add a new sort  

298
00:24:29,840 --> 00:24:35,520
of service? And a big part of that is trying 
to figure out exactly who's going to use it,  

299
00:24:35,520 --> 00:24:43,560
what are the actual real life use cases that 
we know about? Like that I know that Bob from  

300
00:24:43,560 --> 00:24:47,800
Company X has this workflow and this is 
how it would work for him. Here are the  

301
00:24:47,800 --> 00:24:51,800
different variations where it would work. So, 
tying it all the way back to real people is-

302
00:24:51,800 --> 00:24:53,080
Like a specific person?

303
00:24:53,080 --> 00:24:58,320
Yeah, specific person. Yeah. Yeah, 
exactly. Not a hypothetical person.  

304
00:24:58,960 --> 00:25:02,400
Not one that you made up like Alice, Bob, or 
whatever. It's like, "No, here's the first name,  

305
00:25:02,400 --> 00:25:06,280
last name. Here's their email. You can ask them," 
and I think that being able to tie it all the way  

306
00:25:06,280 --> 00:25:13,800
back to reality in that way is a big part of how 
we really think about and discuss these things.

307
00:25:13,800 --> 00:25:17,760
This connects the way I think about my 
newsletter is I always try to answer  

308
00:25:17,760 --> 00:25:21,680
the question a very specific, 
like a person actually asked,  

309
00:25:21,680 --> 00:25:27,600
not a general sense of something people may be 
interested in, and that very specific question,  

310
00:25:27,600 --> 00:25:31,840
like it implies there's a need. Like not 
implies, it proves there's at least one  

311
00:25:31,840 --> 00:25:36,080
person who needs this thing versus you have 
this idea of somebody that may want this thing.

312
00:25:36,080 --> 00:25:40,600
Yeah. I think a trap that a lot of times PMs 
will fall into is they'll make something,  

313
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:45,160
and they'll make some choices in it because maybe 
it's beautiful or it's elegant, but they don't  

314
00:25:45,160 --> 00:25:50,920
go the step of like, "Is reality also beautiful 
and elegant?" Because reality is ugly sometimes,  

315
00:25:50,920 --> 00:25:54,200
and if you have a beautiful and elegant 
solution that doesn't match with reality,  

316
00:25:54,200 --> 00:25:57,400
it doesn't really matter. People can 
look at it, and they can ooh and ah,  

317
00:25:57,400 --> 00:26:01,360
but if they don't use it to get their work done, 
it's never going to have long-term staying power.

318
00:26:01,360 --> 00:26:06,080
Do you have a heuristic of how often 
you need to hear something for you to...  

319
00:26:06,080 --> 00:26:10,000
could be just convinced, this is worth 
investing in? People may hear this, "Oh,  

320
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:12,800
one Bob. Bob wants this featured." 
That doesn't make sense. It's just  

321
00:26:12,800 --> 00:26:17,080
one guy. How do you know when it's like, 
"Okay, we should really invest in this"?

322
00:26:17,080 --> 00:26:21,800
Part of it is you hear something, and you're like, 
"Gosh, that actually is... " Not only is that  

323
00:26:21,800 --> 00:26:26,560
true. It means that the way we thought about this 
was a little bit wrong, and I call this process...  

324
00:26:26,560 --> 00:26:30,640
I don't know if it's the right way to describe 
it. I call it a kneeling where you have a thing,  

325
00:26:30,640 --> 00:26:33,600
and it's not quite the right shape, 
and you put it out into the wild. So,  

326
00:26:33,600 --> 00:26:40,720
this happens way in the first bit of the life 
of a particular feature. You release a thing,  

327
00:26:40,720 --> 00:26:44,560
and then you start getting feedback about 
it, about hey, it doesn't quite fit reality,  

328
00:26:44,560 --> 00:26:50,320
and then you ask yourself like, "Did we test that 
aspect of it? Did we actually match that part to  

329
00:26:50,320 --> 00:26:54,160
reality?" And if you didn't, then it's like that's 
the part where you don't actually need that many  

330
00:26:54,160 --> 00:26:57,440
pieces of feedback against it. It's not really 
a volume thing. It's like, "Did we think about  

331
00:26:57,440 --> 00:27:05,040
this right or wrong?" That's one sort of category.
Another category is just you're getting a request  

332
00:27:05,040 --> 00:27:11,320
for maybe a very big feature or a feature set from 
a lot of different people, but then you dig in,  

333
00:27:11,320 --> 00:27:15,400
and you try to say like, "Okay. Well, tell me 
about how you're trying to use this," and there's  

334
00:27:15,400 --> 00:27:20,440
100 different use cases. So, you have choices 
here. You can either build the big feature that  

335
00:27:20,440 --> 00:27:24,760
covers all the long tail of use cases or you 
can try to see if there's really concentrated  

336
00:27:24,760 --> 00:27:32,600
pools of use cases for this that really make a 
lot of sense to adopt as a first order type of  

337
00:27:32,600 --> 00:27:38,880
feature. So, I think those are the two sort of 
strategies that we employ the most. It's like,  

338
00:27:38,880 --> 00:27:42,440
"Did we think about this wrong? And now we're 
just learning something about how it matches  

339
00:27:42,440 --> 00:27:47,280
reality or for this big general feature that 
people are asking for, are there actually more  

340
00:27:47,280 --> 00:27:52,200
specific use cases that we should be solving, 
and we should be solving really, really well?"

341
00:27:52,200 --> 00:27:57,200
A thread that's coming through so far across 
a lot of these examples is getting to the  

342
00:27:58,320 --> 00:28:04,280
specific person using the thing and making them 
happy and making sure the ask is going to solve  

343
00:28:04,280 --> 00:28:08,840
their actual problem. In the case of looking at 
the IC versus the middle manager, in this case,  

344
00:28:08,840 --> 00:28:14,320
it's like, "Let's talk to the person actually 
asking for this thing," not, "There's like 100  

345
00:28:14,320 --> 00:28:18,200
people generally asking for this thing and let's 
build what we think is a general solution."

346
00:28:18,200 --> 00:28:23,520
Yeah. I'll give you an example of all of 
these things, which we just launched a  

347
00:28:23,520 --> 00:28:30,040
feature called Customer Requests, and basically 
what this does, it adds a new concept of Linear,  

348
00:28:30,040 --> 00:28:37,600
which is a customer. For B2B companies, this 
is very relevant, and the reason we did this  

349
00:28:37,600 --> 00:28:45,240
is because we kept getting this request for 
fully customized fields, and we would be like,  

350
00:28:45,240 --> 00:28:49,920
"Well, what is it that you want with your custom 
fields?" Because the problem is you add 100 custom  

351
00:28:49,920 --> 00:28:54,160
fields and all your ICs start hating it. So, we 
don't want to go down that path, but what is it  

352
00:28:54,160 --> 00:29:01,520
actually you're trying to do? And 40% of them were 
because, "Well, I have a customer," like Walmart  

353
00:29:01,520 --> 00:29:04,240
or whatever, right? Like, "Walmart asked for 
this feature, and it's really important. I need  

354
00:29:04,240 --> 00:29:09,400
everyone to know that Walmart needs this. I need 
to track it. I need to see how have we report... " 

355
00:29:09,400 --> 00:29:14,600
We can report on what have we done for Walmart 
over the past year so that when my CSM has a  

356
00:29:14,600 --> 00:29:18,120
one-on-one conversation with a rep, they can have 
some kind of evidence that we've been doing stuff  

357
00:29:18,120 --> 00:29:23,160
for them, like all this kind of stuff. We're 
like, "Okay. Cool." That sounds like a very  

358
00:29:23,160 --> 00:29:29,000
useful and powerful thing you want to do. How 
do you expect people to tag these things? Well,  

359
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:33,040
manually, because that's how we did it in our 
spreadsheets. It's like, "Okay, instead of that,  

360
00:29:33,040 --> 00:29:36,800
we're going to hook up with your customer support 
tools. We're going to hook up with your CRNs.  

361
00:29:36,800 --> 00:29:40,240
We're going to automatically bring in feedback 
from these companies. We're going to analyze the  

362
00:29:40,240 --> 00:29:44,240
emails where they're from, and then if someone 
requests a feature that gets escalated into  

363
00:29:44,240 --> 00:29:47,720
engineering, it'll just be tagged with whoever 
